SIMPLE: flattery
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flattery
<hw>Flat"ter*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Flatteries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>flaterie</ets>,
OF. <ets>flaterie</ets>, F. <ets>flaterie</ets>, fr. <ets>flater</ets>
to flatter, F. <ets>flatter</ets>; of uncertain origin. See
<er>Flatter</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <def>The act or practice of
flattering; the act of pleasing by artful commendation or compliments;
adulation; false, insincere, or excessive praise.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Just praise is only a debt, but <qex>flattery</qex> is a
present.</q> <rj><qau>Rambler.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Flattery</qex> corrupts both the receiver and the giver.</q>
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Adulation; compliment; obsequiousness. See
<er>Adulation</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flatting</ent>⟦br⟧
